<ArticleLayout
  title="Bathroom Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy"
  description="Before buying bathroom storage, check your space, moisture, ventilation, wall surfaces, vanity size, shower area, towel needs, medicines, cleaning products and daily-use items."
  category="Bathroom"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/bathroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy bathroom with warm finishes, soft light and practical everyday storage"
>
  <p>
    Bathroom storage can look simple until a shelf blocks the towel rail, a shower caddy does
    not suit the surface, an under-sink organiser clashes with pipes, or daily-use products
    end up scattered across the vanity again.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying bathroom shelves, caddies, baskets, drawer organisers, towel rails or
    storage containers, it is worth checking how the bathroom is actually used. Many
    Australian bathrooms are small, shared, humid, awkwardly shaped or used by people with
    very different routines.
  </p>
  <p>
    Useful bathroom storage is not just about fitting more items in. It should keep daily
    items accessible, reduce clutter, suit wet-area conditions and avoid creating new
    problems with moisture, cleaning, access or damage.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide walks through what to measure and check before buying bathroom storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with how the bathroom is used</h2>
  <p>
    Before choosing organisers, decide what the bathroom needs to handle.
  </p>
  <p>
    A main bathroom used by a family has different storage needs from an ensuite, guest
    bathroom, powder room or rental bathroom. A bathroom used by children needs different
    storage from one used mostly by adults. A bathroom with poor ventilation needs more
    caution than one that dries quickly.
  </p>
  <p>Common bathroom uses include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>daily grooming</li>
    <li>showering and bathing</li>
    <li>shaving</li>
    <li>hair styling</li>
    <li>makeup and skincare</li>
    <li>storing towels</li>
    <li>storing toilet paper</li>
    <li>storing cleaning products</li>
    <li>keeping medicines or first-aid items</li>
    <li>managing children's bath items</li>
    <li>storing guest toiletries</li>
    <li>keeping spare bathroom supplies</li>
    <li>handling laundry overflow</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The right storage depends on who uses the bathroom, what needs to be reached daily and
    what should be kept away from moisture, children or pets.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not start by buying matching baskets. Start by understanding what the bathroom
    actually needs to store.
  </p>

  <h2>Sort daily items before buying storage</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom clutter often looks like a storage problem, but it is usually a sorting problem
    first.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying more containers or shelves, group items into simple categories.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Category</th>
        <th>Examples</th>
        <th>Storage implication</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Daily use</td>
        <td>toothbrushes, cleanser, deodorant, hairbrush</td>
        <td>needs easy access</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Weekly use</td>
        <td>face masks, shaving items, hair treatments</td>
        <td>can sit in drawers, baskets or cabinets</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Spare supplies</td>
        <td>soap, toothpaste, toilet paper, razors</td>
        <td>needs labelled backup storage</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Towels</td>
        <td>bath towels, hand towels, face washers</td>
        <td>needs dry, accessible storage</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Cleaning products</td>
        <td>sprays, brushes, cloths</td>
        <td>needs controlled storage and label guidance</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Medicines and first aid</td>
        <td>tablets, creams, bandages</td>
        <td>may need storage away from moisture and children</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Occasional items</td>
        <td>travel toiletries, guest items, special products</td>
        <td>can be stored separately</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Remove or relocate</td>
        <td>expired products, empty bottles, unused items</td>
        <td>should not drive storage purchases</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    This helps you avoid buying storage for items that should be thrown out, used up, donated
    if appropriate, recycled or moved elsewhere.
  </p>

  <h2>Check what should not stay in the bathroom</h2>
  <p>
    Not everything that ends up in a bathroom should be stored there.
  </p>
  <p>
    Bathrooms can be humid and exposed to temperature changes. Some items may not suit
    bathroom storage, especially if ventilation is poor or the room stays damp.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, check whether any items should be moved elsewhere.</p>
  <p>Items to reconsider include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>medicines affected by moisture or heat</li>
    <li>important documents</li>
    <li>spare electronics</li>
    <li>delicate keepsakes</li>
    <li>products that are expired</li>
    <li>products that smell unusual or have changed texture</li>
    <li>makeup or skincare that is no longer used</li>
    <li>large bulk supplies that crowd the room</li>
    <li>cleaning chemicals that children or pets can access</li>
    <li>items stored only because there is no other place for them</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For medicines and first-aid items, follow the product label or pharmacist guidance. Do not
    assume the bathroom is the best storage location.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the vanity first</h2>
  <p>
    The vanity is often the main bathroom storage zone, so measure it before buying
    organisers.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>vanity width</li>
    <li>vanity depth</li>
    <li>cabinet height</li>
    <li>drawer width</li>
    <li>drawer depth</li>
    <li>drawer height</li>
    <li>shelf spacing</li>
    <li>pipe position under the sink</li>
    <li>door hinge clearance</li>
    <li>drawer opening clearance</li>
    <li>whether baskets or organisers block plumbing</li>
    <li>whether products can stand upright</li>
    <li>whether labels remain visible</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Under-sink spaces are often awkward because of pipes, traps, hoses and fixed shelves. Do
    not assume a standard organiser will fit.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the vanity has drawers, measure the internal drawer height before buying trays or
    dividers. Hair brushes, skincare bottles, razors, toothpaste tubes and electric
    toothbrush heads may need different drawer depths.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the area around the basin</h2>
  <p>
    Basin clutter is common because daily items need to be close at hand.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying benchtop organisers, trays or small caddies, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>how much bench space is actually available</li>
    <li>whether items will get splashed</li>
    <li>whether the organiser makes cleaning harder</li>
    <li>whether toothbrushes or razors need airflow</li>
    <li>whether children can reach the items</li>
    <li>whether the organiser blocks the tap, plug or mirror</li>
    <li>whether the area becomes crowded during busy mornings</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A tray can make daily items look tidy, but it can also collect water, dust, toothpaste
    residue and product drips.
  </p>
  <p>
    For small vanities, the better solution may be fewer daily items on the bench rather than
    a larger organiser.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure wall space carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Wall storage can help in a bathroom, but it needs caution.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying wall shelves, cabinets, rails, hooks or adhesive products, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>wall width</li>
    <li>wall height</li>
    <li>nearby tiles</li>
    <li>painted surfaces</li>
    <li>mirror position</li>
    <li>towel rail position</li>
    <li>door swing</li>
    <li>shower screen swing</li>
    <li>power outlet location</li>
    <li>light switch location</li>
    <li>whether the wall is likely to get wet</li>
    <li>whether drilling is allowed</li>
    <li>whether the wall or tile surface suits the product</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not assume adhesive or suction products will suit every surface. Bathroom surfaces may
    be glossy, textured, damp, uneven, dusty, painted, tiled or exposed to heat and moisture.
  </p>
  <p>
    For drilled fixtures, wall cabinets or heavier items, check product instructions, surface
    suitability and whether qualified installation or approval is needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Check shower storage separately</h2>
  <p>
    Shower storage has different requirements from vanity storage because it is exposed to
    water, soap, shampoo, body wash, razors and cleaning.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a shower caddy, shelf, basket or suction organiser, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shower size</li>
    <li>shower screen or curtain position</li>
    <li>shower head and hose position</li>
    <li>tile or glass surface</li>
    <li>whether the surface is textured</li>
    <li>whether the product needs hooks, suction, adhesive or drilling</li>
    <li>how many bottles need storage</li>
    <li>bottle height and weight</li>
    <li>whether water can drain</li>
    <li>whether the caddy will interfere with movement</li>
    <li>whether children can reach razors or products</li>
    <li>whether cleaning will become harder</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A shower organiser that fits the wall but blocks movement or traps water is not a good
    solution.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing too many products in the shower. The more products kept in a wet zone, the
    more cleaning and drainage matter.
  </p>

  <h2>Check towel storage needs</h2>
  <p>
    Towels take up more space than many bathroom products, and they need airflow to dry.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying towel rails, hooks, shelves or baskets, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>how many people use the bathroom</li>
    <li>how many towels are used daily</li>
    <li>whether towels need to dry in the bathroom</li>
    <li>wall space for rails or hooks</li>
    <li>door clearance</li>
    <li>distance from the shower or bath</li>
    <li>whether towels touch the floor</li>
    <li>whether damp towels are being piled together</li>
    <li>ventilation</li>
    <li>whether drilling or adhesive products are allowed</li>
    <li>whether children can hang towels back up</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Towel hooks can save space, but they may not dry towels as evenly as rails in some
    bathrooms. Shelves can hold folded towels, but they may not suit damp towels. Baskets can
    look tidy, but they can also trap damp fabric if used poorly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choose towel storage based on drying, access and space, not just appearance.
  </p>

  <h2>Check moisture and ventilation</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom storage needs to work with moisture, not ignore it.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, check whether the bathroom has:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>an exhaust fan</li>
    <li>a window</li>
    <li>poor airflow</li>
    <li>condensation on mirrors or walls</li>
    <li>damp towels staying wet</li>
    <li>mould-prone corners</li>
    <li>water pooling near the shower or bath</li>
    <li>products getting wet on shelves</li>
    <li>cupboards that smell damp</li>
    <li>timber or particleboard storage near wet areas</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Moisture affects storage choices. Some materials, finishes and baskets may not suit damp
    zones. Closed containers may trap moisture. Open storage may expose items to steam and
    splashes.
  </p>
  <p>
    If there is persistent mould, water damage or ventilation concern, do not treat storage as
    the fix. Seek appropriate advice for the underlying issue.
  </p>

  <h2>Be cautious with over-toilet storage</h2>
  <p>
    Over-toilet storage can be useful in small bathrooms, but it can also create clearance and
    access problems.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying an over-toilet shelf or cabinet, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>toilet width</li>
    <li>cistern height</li>
    <li>total wall height</li>
    <li>seat and lid clearance</li>
    <li>access to flush buttons</li>
    <li>access for cleaning</li>
    <li>whether the unit needs wall fixing</li>
    <li>whether it feels crowded when seated</li>
    <li>whether items could fall</li>
    <li>whether children can reach stored products</li>
    <li>whether the bathroom is humid or poorly ventilated</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid storing heavy, glass, sharp or spill-prone items above the toilet. Also avoid
    placing medicines or cleaning chemicals where they could be reached easily by children.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the unit needs wall fixing, check wall type, product instructions and rental approval
    where relevant.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about children and pets</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom storage can involve items that should not be easy for children or pets to access.
  </p>
  <p>These may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>medicines</li>
    <li>first-aid products</li>
    <li>razors</li>
    <li>blades</li>
    <li>scissors</li>
    <li>hair tools</li>
    <li>cleaning products</li>
    <li>cosmetics</li>
    <li>fragrances</li>
    <li>small items that could be swallowed</li>
    <li>hot styling tools</li>
    <li>glass containers</li>
    <li>bath products</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Before buying open shelves or low baskets, decide what needs controlled storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Open storage can work well for towels and simple daily items. It may not be suitable for
    sharp, hazardous, breakable or sensitive items.
  </p>
  <p>
    For family bathrooms, storage should make careful routines easier, not just make the room
    look tidier.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan for cleaning access</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom storage should not make the room harder to clean.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, check whether it will:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>collect dust</li>
    <li>trap water</li>
    <li>make wiping the vanity harder</li>
    <li>block cleaning around the toilet</li>
    <li>create mould-prone corners</li>
    <li>sit too close to wet zones</li>
    <li>hide leaks or spills</li>
    <li>make the shower harder to scrub</li>
    <li>create clutter around the basin</li>
    <li>block floor mopping</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Storage that creates more cleaning work may not last. In a bathroom, fewer well-placed
    organisers can be better than many small containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choose items that can be moved, wiped, drained or cleaned easily.
  </p>

  <h2>Check renter and body corporate limits</h2>
  <p>
    If you rent or live in a townhouse, unit or body corporate property, check the rules
    before buying bathroom storage that attaches to walls, doors, tiles or fixtures.
  </p>
  <p>You may need approval before:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>drilling into tiles or walls</li>
    <li>installing towel rails</li>
    <li>mounting wall cabinets</li>
    <li>adding fixed shelves</li>
    <li>attaching items to doors</li>
    <li>altering shower fittings</li>
    <li>changing mirrors or fixtures</li>
    <li>installing products that may affect waterproofing or surfaces</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not assume small bathroom changes are allowed. Bathroom surfaces can be expensive to
    repair, especially tiles and waterproofed areas.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renter-friendly bathroom storage usually means freestanding shelves, vanity organisers,
    baskets, over-door storage only where suitable, and removable products only where the
    surface and instructions support them.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide between open and closed storage</h2>
  <p>
    Open and closed storage solve different problems.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Storage type</th>
        <th>Works well for</th>
        <th>Check before buying</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Open shelves</td>
        <td>towels, simple daily items, display items</td>
        <td>moisture, dust, cleaning access</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Closed cabinets</td>
        <td>spare supplies, private items, clutter control</td>
        <td>ventilation, depth, wall fixing</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Drawer organisers</td>
        <td>makeup, grooming items, small products</td>
        <td>drawer height, layout, cleaning</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shower caddies</td>
        <td>shampoo, body wash, soap</td>
        <td>drainage, surface suitability, bottle weight</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Baskets</td>
        <td>towels, spare toilet paper, grouped items</td>
        <td>dampness, labels, cleaning</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Hooks</td>
        <td>towels, robes, selected light items</td>
        <td>surface, load rating, drying</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Over-toilet units</td>
        <td>small bathrooms needing vertical storage</td>
        <td>clearance, stability, wall fixing</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Under-sink organisers</td>
        <td>spare products, grouped bathroom items</td>
        <td>pipes, height, access, spills</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    A practical bathroom often uses a mix. The key is matching the storage to the item and
    the conditions.
  </p>

  <h2>Common bathroom storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>Before buying, avoid these mistakes:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying organisers before sorting expired or unused products</li>
    <li>choosing under-sink storage without measuring around pipes</li>
    <li>using baskets that trap damp towels</li>
    <li>storing medicines in a humid bathroom without checking guidance</li>
    <li>relying on suction products without checking the surface</li>
    <li>using adhesive shelves in wet areas without checking instructions</li>
    <li>blocking the toilet, basin, shower or door swing</li>
    <li>buying benchtop organisers that make cleaning harder</li>
    <li>storing razors or cleaning products within easy child access</li>
    <li>adding over-toilet storage without checking clearance</li>
    <li>assuming all tiles can be drilled</li>
    <li>buying towel hooks without thinking about drying</li>
    <li>storing too many products in the shower</li>
    <li>choosing storage that looks tidy but is difficult to maintain</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A bathroom storage product is only useful if it suits the room, the surfaces, the
    moisture and the daily routine.
  </p>

  <h2>A simple bathroom measuring checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying bathroom storage, write down:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>vanity width, depth and height</li>
    <li>drawer internal dimensions</li>
    <li>under-sink pipe position</li>
    <li>available bench space</li>
    <li>wall width and height</li>
    <li>door swing</li>
    <li>shower screen or curtain movement</li>
    <li>shower caddy area</li>
    <li>towel rail or hook space</li>
    <li>toilet clearance</li>
    <li>over-toilet height and width</li>
    <li>floor space for freestanding storage</li>
    <li>ventilation and moisture issues</li>
    <li>wet zones and splash areas</li>
    <li>tile, wall or glass surfaces</li>
    <li>whether drilling or adhesive products are allowed</li>
    <li>daily-use items</li>
    <li>spare supplies</li>
    <li>towels needed per person</li>
    <li>medicines, razors and cleaning products needing controlled storage</li>
    <li>child and pet access concerns</li>
    <li>rental or body corporate restrictions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Take these notes before buying. Bathroom storage has less room for guesswork than many
    other rooms.
  </p>

  <h2>Our take</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom storage should start with sorting, measuring and moisture checks.
  </p>
  <p>
    Remove expired or unused products first. Measure the vanity, drawers, under-sink area,
    shower, towel space and wall surfaces before buying organisers. Keep daily-use items easy
    to reach, but be more cautious with medicines, razors, cleaning products, damp towels and
    anything placed in wet zones.
  </p>
  <p>
    For most households, practical bathroom storage is simple, cleanable and realistic. It
    should help the bathroom dry, stay usable and reduce clutter without relying on
    questionable adhesives, crowded shelves or storage that blocks access.
  </p>
  <p>
    If a product does not suit the surface, moisture level, rental rules or daily routine, it
    is not the right storage solution no matter how organised it looks.
  </p>

